\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:The-axiomatic-way"

\end_inset

The axiomatic way
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As mentioned above, the pure axiomatic way for proving Euclidean theorems
 is much harder to be automatized than using any of the already listed methods.
 One of the main difficulties is to turn visually obvious facts into precise
 axiomatic statements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are more axiomatic systems which can be used to define plane geometry.
 The most well known are Hilbert's system (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hilbert"

\end_inset

, containing 20 axioms) and Tarski's geometry (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tarski1983"

\end_inset

, with 10 axioms).
 Both systems have already been used to axiomatically prove the most well
 known Euclidean theorems, both manually and in an automatized way.
 However, the (semi-)automatized process of the Euclidean theorems has just
 recently been started by Narboux and his colleagues (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tarski-narboux-2006"

\end_inset

).
 Tarski's system
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Tarski's system
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is investigated in details in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Coq"

\end_inset

.
 Here it is important to emphasize that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Tarski's system has the unusual property that all sentences can be written
 in universal-existential form
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

 This form has all universal quantifiers preceding any existential quantifiers,
 so that all sentences can be recast in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall u\forall v\ldots\exists a\exists b\dots$
\end_inset

 This fact allowed Tarski to prove that Euclidean geometry is decidable:
 there exists an algorithm which can determine the truth or falsity of any
 sentence.
 Tarski's axiomatization is also complete.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
every sentence or its negation is a theorem provable from the axioms.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wiki-tarski"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

