 method, namely that one can get some extra conditions 
\emph on
when exactly
\emph default
 the statement is true.
 In other words, a student may ask a question in a DGS if the given property
 is true in his or her construction, for example if three given lines are
 always concurrent (since he or she already checked a number of cases visually).
 In this case the ATP subsystem may answer 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes, always
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no, never
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but also 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

yes, under certain conditions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, by giving the conditions in a form for the student to understand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since neither the algebraic, nor the axiomatic way is directly applicable
 in teaching argumentation, the other methods (listed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Automated-theorem-proving"

\end_inset

) in-between may be possible alternatives.
 By using the area method, the full-angle method or the GDD method
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
method!--, GDD
\end_layout

\end_inset

 diagrammatical proofs can be produced like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WilsonFleuriot05"

\end_inset

 propose: so-called forward-chaining and backward-chaining proofs can be
 created (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Example-for-diagrammatic"

\end_inset

) by using the output of the full-angle method.
 In a later presentation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WilsonFleuriot06"

\end_inset

