).
 This lays the foundation of the importance for supporting Level 6 verifications
, but a DGS should draw attention to the philosophical difference.
 A positive result for a Level 5 or lower verification can never be the
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sure event
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since all (infinitely many) tests cannot be computed.
 An essential property of mathematics that by using some other ways than
 testing, one can indeed have an overview of 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 cases, and this different way is 
\emph on
proving
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It has to be emphasized that mathematics differs from other sciences in
 this sense.
 Physics, for example, can never be sure that the law of gravity will be
 valid forever.
 Of course, the 
\emph on
idea
\emph default
 of gravity (with mathematics in the background) can be everlasting (actually,
 it 
\emph on
is
\emph default
).
 Other sciences suffer from the same problem.
 Although each science has its role and importance, the strength of mathematics
 is its eternal assertions about the world of ideas, and this property should
 be at least highlighted in the classroom as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However not highlighted yet enough, the presence of numerical errors can
 be crucial in many levels of verification.
 These problems can be worked around by using arbitrary precision floating
 point arithmetics, or integer arithmetics, or symbolic computations.
 There are professional software systems (namely, CAS) which provide advanced
 tools (including a programming language) for defining mathematical problems
 and to solve them efficiently (see 
