 Farmer listed 5 purposes of proving:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
discovery of new logical consequences,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
communication of established logical consequences,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
certification of the truth of logical consequences,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
learning mathematics,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
artistic expression in mathematics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concerning 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

replacing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, Farmer means that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

computer proving in its current form cannot entirely replace traditional
 proving, but computer proving will in time, with suitable advances in mechanize
d mathematics, replace traditional proving just as text editing on a computer
 has replaced typing on a typewriter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To focus on educational aspects, here I highlight Farmer's opinion on the
 current state of computer aided 
\emph on
communication
\emph default
, 
\emph on
learning
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
artistic expression
\emph default
 and the suggested ways of further improvement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Contemporary formal proofs often do not communicate mathematical ideas as
 effectively as informal proofs, because reasoning is done at too low of
 a level and there are too many uninteresting details.
 What is needed: support for transforming a formal proof into a readily
 understandable exposition of the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Computer proving offers students a way to do proving in an interactive environme
nt with explicit “rules of the game”.
 Computer proving can transform how students learn mathematics by enabling
 them to learn mathematics by doing mathematics.
 What is needed: more promotion of this approach and better interactive
 proving environments for students.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since computer proving focuses on syntactic manipulation, artist expression
 is much more difficult in computing proving than in traditional proving.
 What is needed: support for making computing proving look more like traditional
 proving.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My conclusions more or less overlap Farmer's beliefs: his 1st and 3rd suggestion
s are about improving readable proofs, and his 2nd ideas support per theory
 frameworks.
\end_layout

